{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630371"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:15:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:15:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17311"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17311"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10001"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78700"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10001"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17311"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64043"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5528"},{"type":"tags","id":"10754"},{"type":"tags","id":"10755"},{"type":"tags","id":"10757"},{"type":"tags","id":"10759"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23437"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78700"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the assumptions required for Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Non-random mating with selective pressures","Small isolated populations with genetic drift","Random mating with no natural selection pressure","High mutation rate","Steady migration rate into and out of population"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Hardy-Weinberg principle describes the relationship between allele frequencies and genotype frequencies in a population. For this principle to apply, several key assumptions must be met. These are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom mating\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENo mutation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENo migration (gene flow)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo natural selection\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInfinite population size (no genetic drift)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-random mating with selective pressures\u003C/strong\u003E - Both non-random mating and selection violate Hardy-Weinberg assumptions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall isolated populations with genetic drift\u003C/strong\u003E - Genetic drift occurs in small populations, violating the infinite population size assumption\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh mutation rate\u003C/strong\u003E - Mutation changes allele frequencies, violating Hardy-Weinberg assumptions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESteady migration rate into and out of population\u003C/strong\u003E - Migration (gene flow) changes allele frequencies and violates Hardy-Weinberg assumptions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen these assumptions are met, allele frequencies remain stable across generations and genotype frequencies can be predicted using the Hardy-Weinberg equation (p\u00b2 + 2pq + q\u00b2 = 1). Violations of these assumptions indicate that evolution is occurring in the population.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium assumes random mating, no mutation, no migration, no natural selection, and infinite population size.","The Hardy-Weinberg equation (p\u00b2 + 2pq + q\u00b2 = 1) predicts genotype frequencies in a population at equilibrium.","Deviations from Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium suggest evolutionary forces are acting on the population."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Noyes A. Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium and its assumptions. J Genet. 2017;96(2):123-132. doi: 10.1007/s12041-017-0763-3"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64043"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17311"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64043"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T10:04:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T10:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10001"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78700"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji"